+---
+aliases:
+  - shared notifications capability (email + slack)
+status: idea
+created: 2026-05-16
+---
+# Spec [[cat003]] [[cat004]] [[board]]
+
+## problem
+
+Every service (`auth`, `metrics`, `reports`) currently carries its own
+ad-hoc email helper — `auth` shells out to `mail`, `metrics` mixes
+stdout with inline `smtplib`, `reports` pastes another `smtplib`
+snippet. This drift is exactly what `[[adr0003]]` warned about: three
+copy/paste call sites, no retries, no metrics, MTA host changes
+require editing three places. Now the metrics team wants Slack alerts
+and is asking about pager-style SMS for after-hours — adding two more
+channels with the current pattern means six-to-nine copy/paste
+helpers, which is unacceptable.
+
+We want one shared notifications capability the platform provides
+once and many implementations consume — replacing the ad-hoc smtplib
+snippets and adding Slack as a first-class channel.
+
+**Capability boundary.** A small set of horizontal send-channel
+features, each atomic per the AKM `ft###` schema (single `providing`,
+single `api_surface`, single lifecycle). The notifications "platform"
+is **not** one ft### — that would pack three distinct API surfaces
+(SMTP, Slack webhook, SMS gateway) into a single feature with three
+lifecycles. Granularity decision: **2 ft### candidates now, 1
+plausible later** (to be minted at spec-writing time):
+
+- **ft-email-send** — wrap MTA delivery behind one helper
+  (`send_email(to, subject, body)`), inheriting `[[ft002]]` vault for
+  MTA credentials. Replaces the three ad-hoc smtplib snippets.
+  Supersedes the constraint in `[[adr0003]]` (a new ADR overturning
+  adr0003 will be needed at spec stage).
+- **ft-slack-send** — wrap Slack webhook delivery behind one helper
+  (`send_slack(channel, text)`), webhook URL via `[[ft002]]`. New
+  capability; first consumer is the metrics alert path.
+- **ft-sms-send** *(plausible later, not in scope)* — pager-style SMS
+  for after-hours metrics alerts. Mentioned by the metrics team but
+  not committed; deferred until a real on-call rotation story exists
+  (YAGNI). Surfacing it here so future readers see the deliberate
+  cut.
+
+**Why no notifications-router ft###.** A central router (priority,
+retry, multi-channel fan-out) is tempting but premature. With only
+three consumers and two channels, direct adapters compose cleanly.
+A router becomes a separate ft### only when fan-out / templating /
+dedup patterns surface from real usage — not now.
+
+**Plausible consumers (concrete `us###` / service today).**
+
+- `auth` welcome-email path (today: shells to `mail`) → ft-email-send.
+- `reports` CSV-ready notification (today: ad-hoc smtplib, serves
+  `[[pn001]]` "get notified when long-running reports finish", a goal
+  on the analyst persona; would unblock a future `us###` formalizing
+  the notification AC) → ft-email-send.
+- `metrics` alert path (today: stdout + ad-hoc smtplib) → both
+  ft-email-send and ft-slack-send, channel chosen by alert
+  severity/route.
+- `[[us003]]` rotate-credentials platform story — a plausible
+  consumer for ops alerts during rotation windows. Not committed.
+
+**Migration targets (ad-hoc → feature).**
+
+- `src/services/auth/__init__.py` — welcome-email shell-out →
+  ft-email-send. Comment in code already flags this migration.
+- `src/services/metrics/__init__.py` — alert smtplib + stdout →
+  ft-email-send + ft-slack-send.
+- `src/services/reports/__init__.py` — CSV-email smtplib →
+  ft-email-send.
+
+Migration cost is small per site (one-call swap) but requires a new
+ADR superseding `[[adr0003]]` — that ADR explicitly forbids a relay /
+shared helper, so the constraint has to flip before the features
+ship.
+
+**Constraints inherited from categories.**
+
+- `[[cat003]]` (infrastructure) — `[[adr0003]]` binds the current
+  smtplib-direct policy; new ADR needed to overturn before
+  ft-email-send can supersede the snippets.
+- `[[cat004]]` (observability) — no binding ADR today; alert routing
+  policy will likely produce a new ADR during spec-writing.
+- `[[ft002]]` (vault-secrets) — MTA creds, Slack webhook URL, future
+  SMS gateway token all retrieved via `secret()`. Each new ft###
+  inherits ft002's constraints automatically.
+
+**Out of scope for this sp###.** Templating, dedup, rate-limiting,
+priority routing, fan-out, retry policy beyond a single retry,
+delivery receipts, opt-out lists. These are router-level concerns
+and explicitly deferred until usage patterns demand them.
+
+**Intent at spec-writing stage.** Mint two new `ft###` (email-send,
+slack-send), write the new ADR superseding `[[adr0003]]`, draft
+migration tasks for the three services. The split between
+ft-email-send and ft-slack-send work lands at task level during
+`spec-refinement` / `spec-ready` — keeping it in one sp### avoids
+fragmenting a small, coherent scaffolding effort across two board
+lifecycles.
+
